  "prompt": "How much, if at all, will cotton khakis shrink when washed?",
  "response": "Cotton khakis can shrink to some extent when washed, especially if they are made from 100% cotton. The amount of shrinkage depends on several factors:\n\n1. **Fabric Composition**: 100% cotton khakis are more prone to shrinkage compared to blends that include synthetic fibers like polyester or elastane, which help reduce shrinkage.\n\n2. **Washing Temperature**: Hot water is more likely to cause shrinkage than cold or warm water. Washing in cold water can help minimize shrinkage.\n\n3. **Drying Method**: Machine drying on high heat is the most common cause of shrinkage. Air-drying or using a low-heat setting can help preserve the original size and shape.\n\n4. **Pre-shrunk Fabric**: Many khakis are labeled as \"pre-shrunk,\" meaning they have undergone a manufacturing process to reduce further shrinkage. Pre-shrunk khakis will still shrink slightly, but much less than untreated cotton.\n\nOn average, untreated 100% cotton khakis can shrink by about 3-5% in total, which translates to about 1-2 inches in length and a slight reduction in width. Pre-shrunk khakis might shrink by 1-3% or less, depending on care.\n\n### Tips to Minimize Shrinkage:\n- Wash in cold water.\n- Use a gentle cycle.\n- Air-dry or tumble dry on low heat.\n- Avoid overloading the washing machine to prevent excessive agitation.\n\nIf you\u2019re concerned about shrinkage, check the care label on your khakis and follow the recommended washing and drying instructions.",
